<body>
<div class="page">

  <!-- HEADER -->
  <div class="header">
    <div class="header-label">NYC Regents Chemistry · Major Topic I</div>
    <div class="header-title">Atomic Structure</div>
    <div class="header-meta">
      <span>⏱ 1.5 Hours</span>
      <span>📋 12 Things to Know</span>
      <span>📐 6 Skills to Master</span>
      <span>🔬 Reference Table S &amp; T</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- LESSON TIMELINE -->
  <div class="timeline">
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-time">0:00 – 0:20</div>
      <div class="tl-label">Atomic structure &amp; subatomic particles</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-time">0:20 – 0:35</div>
      <div class="tl-label">Rutherford + atomic number / mass number</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-time">0:35 – 0:50</div>
      <div class="tl-label">Isotopes + weighted average atomic mass</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-time">0:50 – 1:10</div>
      <div class="tl-label">Energy levels, electron config &amp; excited state</div>
    </div>
    <div class="tl-item">
      <div class="tl-time">1:10 – 1:30</div>
      <div class="tl-label">Bright-line spectra, ions &amp; practice problems</div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 1 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">1</div>
      <div class="section-title">Subatomic Particles</div>
      <div class="section-time">0:00 – 0:20</div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-blue">
      <strong>Big idea:</strong> All atoms are made of three subatomic particles. You MUST know their mass, charge, and location. This comes up almost every Regents exam.
    </div>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Particle</th>
          <th>Symbol</th>
          <th>Charge</th>
          <th>Mass (amu)</th>
          <th>Location</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Proton</strong></td>
          <td>p⁺</td>
          <td>+1</td>
          <td>≈ 1</td>
          <td>Nucleus</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Neutron</strong></td>
          <td>n⁰</td>
          <td>0 (neutral)</td>
          <td>≈ 1</td>
          <td>Nucleus</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td><strong>Electron</strong></td>
          <td>e⁻</td>
          <td>–1</td>
          <td>≈ 0 (negligible)</td>
          <td>Electron cloud (outside nucleus)</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="alert alert-gold">
      <strong>⚡ Regents tip:</strong> Electrons have negligible mass — they do NOT contribute to mass number. The nucleus (protons + neutrons) holds nearly all of the atom's mass.
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Wave-Mechanical Model</div>
      <p>The modern model of the atom says electrons do <strong>not</strong> travel in fixed circular orbits. Instead, they exist in <strong>orbitals</strong> — regions of space where there is a high probability of finding an electron.</p>
      <p>Think of an orbital like a "fuzzy cloud" rather than a planet orbit.</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 2 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">2</div>
      <div class="section-title">Rutherford's Gold Foil Experiment</div>
      <div class="section-time">0:20 – 0:35</div>
    </div>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">What he did</div>
        <p>Rutherford fired positively charged alpha (α) particles at a thin sheet of gold foil and observed where they went using a detector screen.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="card">
        <div class="card-title">What he expected</div>
        <p>Based on the "plum pudding" model, he expected all particles to pass straight through with minor deflection — the positive charge was thought to be spread out.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">3 Key Conclusions (memorize these!)</div>
      <div class="vocab">
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">Most passed through →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">Atoms are mostly empty space</div>
        </div>
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">Some deflected →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">There is a small, dense, positively charged center</div>
        </div>
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">A few bounced back →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">The nucleus contains most of the atom's mass and has a positive charge that repels α particles</div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-red">
      <strong>❌ Common mistake:</strong> Rutherford did NOT discover electrons — that was J.J. Thomson. Rutherford discovered the nucleus.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 3 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">3</div>
      <div class="section-title">Atomic Number, Mass Number &amp; Identity</div>
      <div class="section-time">0:20 – 0:35</div>
    </div>

    <div class="formula-box">
      Atomic Number (Z)  =  # of protons<br>
      Mass Number (A)    =  # of protons + # of neutrons<br>
      # of Neutrons      =  Mass Number − Atomic Number<br>
      Neutral atom: # of protons = # of electrons
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-green">
      <strong>🔑 Key rule:</strong> The <strong>identity</strong> of an element is determined entirely by its number of protons (atomic number). Change the protons → different element. Change the neutrons → still the same element (isotope). Change the electrons → ion.
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Isotope Notation — How to read it</div>
      <div style="text-align:center; padding: 1rem 0;">
        <svg width="180" height="80" viewBox="0 0 180 80">
          <text x="90" y="50" font-family="JetBrains Mono, monospace" font-size="36" font-weight="700" fill="#1A3A5C" text-anchor="middle">C</text>
          <text x="60" y="32" font-family="JetBrains Mono, monospace" font-size="16" font-weight="600" fill="#C0392B" text-anchor="middle">12</text>
          <text x="60" y="55" font-family="JetBrains Mono, monospace" font-size="14" fill="#C0392B" text-anchor="middle">6</text>
          <text x="8" y="28" font-family="DM Sans, sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#6B6B6B">Mass number</text>
          <text x="2" y="56" font-family="DM Sans, sans-serif" font-size="9" fill="#6B6B6B">Atomic number</text>
          <line x1="30" y1="26" x2="52" y2="30" stroke="#C0392B" stroke-width="0.8"/>
          <line x1="30" y1="54" x2="52" y2="52" stroke="#C0392B" stroke-width="0.8"/>
        </svg>
      </div>
      <p style="text-align:center; font-size:13px; color:var(--muted);">Carbon-12: 6 protons, 6 neutrons, 6 electrons (if neutral)</p>
    </div>

    <div class="example">
      <div class="example-label">Practice — Try it</div>
      <p>For ¹⁴₆C (Carbon-14):</p>
      <p>Protons = 6 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Neutrons = 14 − 6 = <strong>8</strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; Electrons (neutral) = 6</p>
      <p style="margin-top:6px;">For ¹⁶₈O²⁻ (Oxide ion):</p>
      <p>Protons = 8 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Neutrons = 8 &nbsp;|&nbsp; Electrons = 8 + 2 = <strong>10</strong> &nbsp;|&nbsp; Charge = –2</p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 4 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">4</div>
      <div class="section-title">Isotopes &amp; Atomic Mass</div>
      <div class="section-time">0:35 – 0:50</div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">What is an isotope?</div>
      <p>Isotopes are atoms of the <strong>same element</strong> (same # of protons) that have <strong>different masses</strong> because they have a <strong>different number of neutrons</strong>.</p>
      <p style="margin-top:8px;">Examples: Carbon-12 (6p, 6n), Carbon-13 (6p, 7n), Carbon-14 (6p, 8n) — all carbon, all different masses.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Atomic Mass (Weighted Average)</div>
      <p>The atomic mass on the periodic table is <strong>NOT</strong> a whole number because it is the <strong>weighted average</strong> of all naturally occurring isotopes of that element.</p>

      <div class="formula-box">
        Atomic Mass = Σ (isotope mass × fractional abundance)
      </div>

      <div class="example">
        <div class="example-label">Worked Example — Chlorine</div>
        <p>Cl-35 is 75.77% abundant &nbsp;|&nbsp; Cl-37 is 24.23% abundant</p>
        <p style="margin-top:6px; font-family: JetBrains Mono, monospace; font-size:13px;">
          = (35 × 0.7577) + (37 × 0.2423)<br>
          = 26.52 + 8.97<br>
          = <strong>35.45 amu</strong> ✓ (matches periodic table)
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-gold">
      <strong>⚡ Regents tip:</strong> The atomic mass is always closer to the mass of the more abundant isotope. Use this to check your answer!
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 5 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">5</div>
      <div class="section-title">Energy Levels &amp; Electron Configuration</div>
      <div class="section-time">0:50 – 1:10</div>
    </div>

    <div class="vocab" style="margin-bottom:1rem;">
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-term">Principal energy levels</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">The main energy levels (shells) of an atom, numbered 1, 2, 3, 4… outward from the nucleus. Also called electron shells.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-term">Valence shell</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">The outermost electron shell. Electrons here have the <strong>most energy</strong> and are most involved in chemical reactions.</div>
      </div>
      <div class="vocab-item">
        <div class="vocab-term">Valence electrons</div>
        <div class="vocab-def">Electrons in the valence shell. For main group elements, = group number on the periodic table.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Energy Level (n)</th>
          <th>Max electrons</th>
          <th>Sublevels</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>1</td><td>2</td><td>s</td></tr>
        <tr><td>2</td><td>8</td><td>s, p</td></tr>
        <tr><td>3</td><td>18</td><td>s, p, d</td></tr>
        <tr><td>4</td><td>32</td><td>s, p, d, f</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Ground State vs. Excited State</div>

      <div class="divider">Ground State</div>
      <p style="font-size:14px; margin-bottom:8px;">Electrons fill the <strong>lowest available energy levels first</strong> (Aufbau principle). This is the most stable, lowest energy arrangement.</p>
      <div class="config-row">
        <span style="font-size:13px; color:var(--muted);">Na (11e⁻):</span>
        <div class="config-box filled">1s²</div>
        <div class="config-box filled">2s²</div>
        <div class="config-box filled">2p⁶</div>
        <div class="config-box filled">3s¹</div>
        <span style="font-size:12px; color:#27AE60;">✓ Ground state</span>
      </div>

      <div class="divider">Excited State</div>
      <p style="font-size:14px; margin-bottom:8px;">An electron has <strong>absorbed energy</strong> and jumped to a higher energy level, skipping a lower level. This is unstable — the atom will release light to return to ground state.</p>
      <div class="config-row">
        <span style="font-size:13px; color:var(--muted);">Na (excited):</span>
        <div class="config-box filled">1s²</div>
        <div class="config-box filled">2s²</div>
        <div class="config-box filled">2p⁶</div>
        <div class="config-box empty">3s⁰</div>
        <div class="config-box excited">4s¹</div>
        <span style="font-size:12px; color:#C0392B;">⚠ Excited state (skipped 3s!)</span>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-green">
      <strong>✅ How to identify excited state:</strong> Look for an electron in a higher level when a lower level is not fully filled. If 3s is empty but 4s has an electron — that's excited state.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 6 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">6</div>
      <div class="section-title">Bright-Line Spectra &amp; Light</div>
      <div class="section-time">1:10 – 1:20</div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">How light is produced by atoms</div>
      <div class="vocab">
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">Step 1 →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">Atom absorbs energy → electron jumps to a higher (excited) energy level</div>
        </div>
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">Step 2 →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">Electron is unstable in excited state → falls back to a lower energy level (ground state)</div>
        </div>
        <div class="vocab-item">
          <div class="vocab-term">Step 3 →</div>
          <div class="vocab-def">The energy difference is released as a <strong>photon of light</strong></div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">Bright-Line Spectrum</div>
      <p style="margin-bottom:8px;">Each element produces a <strong>unique set of colored lines</strong> (bright-line spectrum) — like a fingerprint for that element. This is because each element has unique energy level differences.</p>

      <!-- Simplified spectrum graphic -->
      <div style="background:#111; border-radius:6px; padding:12px 16px; margin:10px 0; overflow:hidden;">
        <div style="font-size:10px; color:#aaa; margin-bottom:6px; font-family: JetBrains Mono, monospace;">Hydrogen bright-line spectrum</div>
        <div style="position:relative; height:28px; background: linear-gradient(to right, #1a0030 0%, #1a0030 100%);">
          <div style="position:absolute; left:18%; width:2px; height:100%; background:#7B2FBE; opacity:0.9;"></div>
          <div style="position:absolute; left:31%; width:2px; height:100%; background:#4169E1; opacity:0.9;"></div>
          <div style="position:absolute; left:60%; width:3px; height:100%; background:#00CED1; opacity:0.9;"></div>
          <div style="position:absolute; left:78%; width:3px; height:100%; background:#FF4500; opacity:0.9;"></div>
        </div>
        <div style="display:flex; justify-content:space-between; font-size:9px; color:#666; margin-top:4px; font-family: JetBrains Mono, monospace;">
          <span>400 nm (violet)</span><span>700 nm (red)</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p style="font-size:13px; color:var(--muted);">Each line = a specific wavelength of light emitted when an electron falls a specific number of energy levels. More energy difference → shorter wavelength → toward violet end.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-gold">
      <strong>⚡ Regents tip:</strong> On the exam, you may be shown a spectrum and asked to identify the element — match the pattern of lines to the reference spectrum. Each element's pattern is unique.
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- ═══ SECTION 7 ═══ -->
  <div class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <div class="section-num">7</div>
      <div class="section-title">Ions — Calculating Charge</div>
      <div class="section-time">1:20 – 1:30</div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-title">What is an ion?</div>
      <p>An ion is an atom (or group of atoms) that has gained or lost electrons, giving it a net charge.</p>

      <div class="formula-box">
        Charge = # of protons − # of electrons<br><br>
        Positive ion (cation): lost electrons → more protons than electrons<br>
        Negative ion (anion): gained electrons → more electrons than protons
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="two-col">
      <div class="example">
        <div class="example-label">Cation Example</div>
        <p><strong>Na⁺</strong></p>
        <p>Protons: 11</p>
        <p>Electrons: 10 (lost 1)</p>
        <p>Charge = 11 − 10 = <strong>+1</strong></p>
      </div>
      <div class="example">
        <div class="example-label">Anion Example</div>
        <p><strong>Cl⁻</strong></p>
        <p>Protons: 17</p>
        <p>Electrons: 18 (gained 1)</p>
        <p>Charge = 17 − 18 = <strong>–1</strong></p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="alert alert-red">
      <strong>❌ Common mistake:</strong> Ions do NOT have a different atomic number or mass number. Only the electron count changes. A Na⁺ ion still has 11 protons and is still sodium.
    </div>
  </div>

